Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Halve, peel, and grate
@yellow onion{1} with a #box grater{}. Grate @zucchini{1} into a #medium bowl{}.

Add @ground beef{16%ounce}, @panko breadcrumbs{1%cup}, half the onions, @egg{1},
and 1 Tablespoon @italian seasoning{2%tablespoon} to #bowl{} with zucchini.
(Keep the other @egg{1} for another day.) Season generously with @salt{1%teaspoon}
and @pepper{}. Combine thoroughly with your hands, and form into four large
meatballs.

Bake the mega meatballs: Place meatballs on a lightly oiled #baking sheet{}.
Bake until no pink remains, about ~{20%minutes}.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{4%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium
heat. Add @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, remaining onions, and 1 Tablespoon
italian seasoning. Toss until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Season with salt and
pepper. Add @crushed tomatoes{2%box} and ½ cup water. Simmer over low heat
until rest of meal is ready. Season to taste with up to 1 teaspoon @sugar{1%tsp}
and a generous pinch of salt and pepper.

Bring 4 cups water to a boil in a #medium pot{}. Once boiling, add
@polenta{1%cup} and whisk constantly until thickened. Add more water, as
necessary, to reach a creamy consistency. Stir in @parmesan cheese{½%cup} and
@butter{1%tablespoon}. Season generously with salt and pepper.

> TIP: If polenta firms up before you're ready to serve, simply reheat and whisk
> in a bit more water.

Finish and serve: When the mega meatballs are done, sprinkle with
@mozzarella cheese{1%cup} and return to oven for ~{1-2%minutes}, until fully
melted. Plate the creamy polenta, and top with marinara sauce and a mega
meatball. Enjoy!